11 COMMITTEE SUBSTITUTE
12 An Act relating to schools; amending 70 O.S. 2021,
Section 1-109, as last amended by Section 1, Chapter
13 480, O.S.L. 2025 (70 O.S. Supp. 2025, Section 1-109),
which relates to the length of the school year;
14 prohibiting school districts from counting
professional meetings and parent-teacher conferences
15 toward classroom instruction time; amending 70 O.S.
2021, Section 1210.545, as amended by Section 2,
16 Chapter 412, O.S.L. 2025 (70 O.S. Supp. 2025, Section
1210.545), which relates to the Oklahoma School
17 Testing Program; eliminating reference to the use of
classroom instruction time for certain meetings and
18 conferences; and providing an effective date.
19
20
21 BE IT ENACTED BY THE PEOPLE OF THE STATE OF OKLAHOMA:
22 SECTION 1. AMENDATORY 70 O.S. 2021, Section 1-109, as
23 last amended by Section 1, Chapter 480, O.S.L. 2025 (70 O.S. Supp.
24 2025, Section 1-109), is amended to read as follows:
HB3151 HFLR Page 1
BOLD FACE denotes Committee Amendments.

1 Section 1-109. A. For all public schools in this state, school
2 shall actually be in session and classroom instruction offered:
3 1. For not less than one hundred eighty-one (181) days;
4 2. For not less than one thousand eighty-six (1,086) hours each
5 school year, if a district board of education adopts a school-hours
6 policy and notifies the State Board of Education prior to October 15
7 of the applicable school year;
8 3. Beginning with the 2025-2026 school year, for not less than
9 one thousand eighty-six (1,086) hours with a minimum of one hundred
10 sixty-six (166) days of instruction each school year, if a district
11 board of education adopts a school-hours policy and notifies the
12 State Board of Education prior to October 15 of the applicable
13 school year; or
14 4. Beginning with the 2025-2026 school year, for not less than
15 one thousand eighty-six (1,086) hours each school year, if a
16 district board of education adopts a school-hours policy, notifies
17 the State Board of Education prior to October 15 of the applicable
18 school year, and meets the requirements established by the State
19 Board of Education pursuant to subsection H of this section.
20 B. A school district may shall not count more than thirty (30)
21 hours each school year that are used for attendance of professional
22 meetings toward the one hundred eighty-one (181) days or one
23 thousand eighty-six (1,086) hours of classroom instruction time
24 required in subsection A of this section.
HB3151 HFLR Page 2
BOLD FACE denotes Committee Amendments.

1 C. Teachers off contract with an employing district shall not
2 be required by the employing school district to attend professional
3 meetings unless the teacher is paid additional compensation for the
4 additional time. Teachers may be paid additional compensation for
5 attending professional meetings in excess of their contract term.
6 Subject to district board of education policy or collective
7 bargaining agreement, additional paid professional days may be
8 granted for individual teachers to attend or participate in
9 professional meetings, staff development training, or National Board
10 certification portfolio development as provided for in Section 6-
11 204.2 of this title.
12 D. A school district may authorize parent-teacher conferences
13 to be held during a regular school day. If authorized by the school
14 district, parent-teacher conferences shall not be counted as
15 classroom instruction time for no more than six (6) hours per
16 semester, for a total of twelve (12) hours per school year.
17 E. A school district may maintain school for less than a full
18 school year only when conditions beyond the control of school
19 authorities make the maintenance of the term impossible and the
20 State Board of Education has been apprised and has expressed
21 concurrence in writing.
22 F. The State Board of Education shall establish criteria for an
23 extended-day schedule for schools subject to paragraph 1 of
24 subsection A of this section. The criteria shall:
HB3151 HFLR Page 3
BOLD FACE denotes Committee Amendments.

1 1. Prescribe a lengthened school day within limits determined
2 not to be detrimental to quality instruction;
3 2. Ensure that the schedule is equivalent in annual hours of
4 instruction to the one-hundred-eighty-one-day school year specified
5 in paragraph 1 of subsection A of this section; and
6 3. Be consistent with the provisions of this section and
7 Sections 1-111 and 1-112 of this title but may result in fewer
8 annual days of instruction.
9 G. Notwithstanding the provisions of subsection F of this
10 section, a school district board of education subject to paragraph 1
11 of subsection A of this section may adopt and implement an extended-
12 day schedule subject to the following requirements:
13 1. The annual number of hours of instruction shall equal or
14 exceed one thousand eighty-six (1,086) hours, which is the
15 equivalent of one hundred eighty-one (181) days of instruction as
16 specified in subsection A of this section for six (6) hours each day
17 as specified in Section 1-111 of this title;
18 2. The annual number of days of instruction shall equal or
19 exceed one hundred eighty-one (181) days as specified in subsection
20 A of this section;
21 3. The schedule adopted shall be consistent with the provisions
22 of Sections 1-111 and 1-112 of this title, except that for not more
23 than one (1) day per week, a school day shall consist of not less
24
HB3151 HFLR Page 4
BOLD FACE denotes Committee Amendments.

1 than five (5) hours devoted to academic instruction in a regular
2 classroom setting;
3 4. The district shall hold a public hearing prior to the
4 adoption of an extended-day schedule authorized pursuant to this
5 subsection; and
6 5. The district shall document the impact on student
7 achievement as determined by the academic performance data score and
8 any other relevant factors that are a result of implementation of an
9 extended-day schedule authorized pursuant to this subsection and
10 provide an annual report to the State Board of Education of the
11 results. If improvement in student achievement cannot be documented
12 in the report, the district board of education shall revoke
13 authorization as provided by this subsection. If the district board
14 of education does not revoke authorization after student achievement
15 is not documented in the report, the State Board of Education may
16 deny accreditation of any school in violation of this subsection.
17 H. Beginning with the 2021-2022 school year, a school district
18 board of education may adopt a school-hours policy as provided for
19 by paragraph 4 of subsection A of this section only if it meets or
20 exceeds the minimum guidelines for student performance and school
21 district cost savings established by the State Board of Education.
22 The State Board of Education shall promulgate rules, subject to
23 approval by the Legislature, establishing the minimum guidelines for
24 student performance and school district cost savings.
HB3151 HFLR Page 5
BOLD FACE denotes Committee Amendments.

1 I. If subject to paragraph 2 of subsection A of this section, a
2 district board of education or designee may elect to close a school
3 during the school day for inclement weather purposes. In such an
4 event, the number of hours incurred in classroom instruction time
5 prior to school closure shall be counted toward the one thousand
6 eighty-six (1,086) hours per year requirement.
7 J. 1. Except as provided for in paragraph 2 of this
8 subsection, beginning with the 2026-2027 school year a school
9 district or charter school shall not count days or portions of days
10 when school is closed and virtual instruction is provided toward the
11 one hundred eighty-one (181) days or one thousand eighty-six (1,086)
12 hours of classroom instruction time required by subsection A of this
13 section. For the purposes of this subsection, "virtual instruction"
14 means the use of the Internet or other digital information
15 transmission systems as a form of instruction.
16 2. Beginning with the 2026-2027 school year, a school district
17 or charter school may count up to two (2) days or twelve (12) hours
18 when school is closed and virtual instruction is provided toward the
19 one hundred eighty-one (181) days or one thousand eighty-six (1,086)
20 hours of classroom instruction time required by subsection A of this
21 section only if:
22 a. the Superintendent of Public Instruction has approved
23 the virtual instruction plan submitted by a school
24 district board of education or charter school
HB3151 HFLR Page 6
BOLD FACE denotes Committee Amendments.

1 governing board. A school district board of education
2 or charter school governing board shall approve its
3 virtual instruction plan, publish the plan on the
4 website for the school district or charter school, and
5 submit it to the Superintendent of Public Instruction
6 by November 1, 2025. The Superintendent shall approve
7 or disapprove all submitted virtual instruction plans
8 by January 31, 2026. A school district board of
9 education or charter school governing board shall
10 review its virtual instruction plan annually and
11 approve any necessary revisions for submission to the
12 Superintendent of Public Instruction by November 1
13 each subsequent year, and the Superintendent shall
14 approve or disapprove submitted plans by January 31
15 each subsequent year. If a plan is disapproved, the
16 school district board of education or charter school
17 governing board may approve a revised plan, publish it
18 on the website for the school district or charter
19 school, and submit it to the Superintendent. The plan
20 shall include a virtual needs assessment which shall
21 address availability of technology infrastructure to
22 deliver virtual instruction. The plan shall also
23 address how the school district or charter school
24 plans to provide:
HB3151 HFLR Page 7
BOLD FACE denotes Committee Amendments.

1 (1) instruction to students on an Individualized
2 Education Program (IEP),
3 (2) child nutrition services, and
4 (3) transportation for students enrolled in
5 technology center school courses or programs,
6 b. a state of emergency or proclamation has been issued
7 by the Governor for a specific reason relating to
8 school district or charter school operations, and
9 c. the school district board of education or charter
10 school governing board approves the use of virtual
11 instruction.
12 3. The provisions of this subsection shall not apply to
13 statewide virtual charter schools or full-time virtual education
14 programs operated by a school district.
15 K. By June 30, 2027, and by June 30 each subsequent year, the
16 State Department of Education shall publish on its website and
17 electronically submit to the Governor, the President Pro Tempore of
18 the Senate, and the Speaker of the House of Representatives a report
19 with information regarding the use of virtual instruction as
20 authorized by subsection J of this section. The report shall
21 include, at a minimum:
22 1. The school districts and charter schools that closed school
23 and provided virtual instruction as authorized by subsection J of
24
HB3151 HFLR Page 8
BOLD FACE denotes Committee Amendments.

1 this section and the length of time virtual instruction was
2 provided; and
3 2. The reason for which school was closed and virtual
4 instruction was provided.
5 L. Nothing in this section shall be construed as affecting the
6 right of an employing school district to require teachers as defined
7 in Section 6-101.3 of this title to work in excess of the one
8 thousand eighty-six (1,086) hours required for student instruction.
9 In addition, nothing in this section shall be construed to affect
10 the Fair Labor Standards Act of 1938 status of any school district
11 employee.
12 M. The provisions of this section shall not prohibit the
13 Oklahoma School for the Blind or the Oklahoma School for the Deaf
14 from adopting an alternative school-hours policy if the Oklahoma
15 School for the Blind or the Oklahoma School for the Deaf notifies
16 and receives approval from the State Board of Education prior to
17 October 15 of the applicable school year.
18 SECTION 2. AMENDATORY 70 O.S. 2021, Section 1210.545, as
19 amended by Section 2, Chapter 412, O.S.L. 2025 (70 O.S. Supp. 2025,
20 Section 1210.545), is amended to read as follows:
21 Section 1210.545. A. Except as otherwise provided, as part of
22 the accountability system developed as provided for in Section
23 1210.541 of this title, the State Board of Education shall prepare
24 annual reports of the results of the Oklahoma School Testing Program
HB3151 HFLR Page 9
BOLD FACE denotes Committee Amendments.

1 whic h describe student achievement in the state, and each school
2 site, pursuant to the Elementary and Secondary Education Act of 1965
3 (ESEA) as reauthorized by P.L. No. 114-95, also known as the Every
4 Student Succeeds Act (ESSA), and any related federal regulations.
5 B. The annual report as required pursuant to subsection A of
6 this section shall identify school sites as having one of the
7 following grades for each indicator, separately, and by a single
8 overview grade of all indicators, defined according to rules of the
9 State Board of Education:
10 1. "A" means schools making excellent progress;
11 2. "B" means schools making above average progress;
12 3. "C" means schools making satisfactory progress;
13 4. "D" means schools making less than satisfactory progress;
14 and
15 5. "F" means schools failing to make adequate progress.
16 C. Each school that has students who are tested and included in
17 the school grading system as provided for in this section shall
18 receive a school grade, except as follows:
19 1. A school shall not receive a school grade if the number of
20 students tested and included in the school grading system is less
21 than the minimum sample size necessary for statistical reliability
22 and prevention of the unlawful release of personally identifiable
23 student data. The State Board of Education is directed to establish
24
HB3151 HFLR Page 10
BOLD FACE denotes Committee Amendments.

1 the lowest minimum sample size necessary to meet the requirements of
2 this paragraph; and
3 2. The academic performance of students who are enrolled full-
4 time in an online program that is offered by a school district or
5 charter school that is not the district of residence or is not
6 located in the district of residence of the student shall be
7 reported separately by the school district or charter school and
8 shall not be included when determining the grade of the school site
9 or charter school.
10 D. The State Board of Education may adopt alternate systems of
11 accountability for statewide virtual charter schools, alternative
12 education programs as defined in Section 1210.568 of this title, and
13 schools serving only grades prekindergarten or kindergarten through
14 two.
15 E. The grade of a school shall be based on a multimeasures
16 approach to accountability in accordance with the Elementary and
17 Secondary Education Act of 1965 (ESEA) as reauthorized by P.L. No.
18 114-95, also known as the Every Student Succeeds Act (ESSA) and any
19 federal regulations that include, but are not limited to, the
20 following indicators:
21 1. Statewide assessments including the establishment of student
22 performance bands;
23 2. Graduation rates for high schools;
24
HB3151 HFLR Page 11
BOLD FACE denotes Committee Amendments.

1 3. Statewide academic measures for elementary and middle
2 schools;
3 4. English language proficiency for English learners; and
4 5. At least one additional statewide measure of school quality
5 or student success including, but not limited to, school climate,
6 school safety, student engagement, educator engagement, and/or
7 advanced coursework and postsecondary readiness. Chronic
8 absenteeism shall not be included as a statewide measure of school
9 quality or student success.
10 F. The grade of an elementary or middle school site shall
11 include, but not be limited to:
12 1. Up to forty (40) points based on a measure of status for
13 English language arts (ELA), math, and science;
14 2. Up to thirty-five (35) points based on growth in ELA and
15 math; and
16 3. Up to ten (10) points based on English language proficiency
17 assessment (ELPA) progress.
18 G. The grade of a high school site shall include, but not be
19 limited to:
20 1. Up to fifty-five (55) points based on a measure of status
21 for English language arts (ELA), math, and science;
22 2. Up to ten (10) points based on English language proficiency
23 assessment (ELPA) progress;
24 3. Up to ten (10) points based on the graduation rate; and
HB3151 HFLR Page 12
BOLD FACE denotes Committee Amendments.

1 4. Up to ten (10) points based on postsecondary opportunities.
2 For purposes of this section, postsecondary opportunities shall
3 include advanced placement, International Baccalaureate, dual and
4 concurrent enrollment, scoring Silver level or above on American
5 College Testing (ACT) WorkKeys, internships, mentorships and
6 apprenticeships, military readiness as evidenced by being accepted
7 for enlistment into any branch of the military within the first year
8 after high school graduation or earning a military readiness score
9 on the Armed Services Vocational Aptitude Battery (ASVAB), and
10 industry certifications. The Board shall adopt a timeline for
11 moving from completion of such opportunities to crediting
12 achievement of such opportunities.
13 H. Elementary, middle, and high school sites shall be eligible
14 for the following bonus point amounts to be used in the calculation
15 of the site's single overview grade:
16 1. Up to three (3) bonus points if the school site provides in-
17 person classroom instruction in excess of the requirements of
18 paragraphs 1 and 2 of subsection A of Section 1-109 of this title,
19 not including in-person classroom instruction time used for
20 professional development or parent-teacher conferences; and
21 2. Up to two (2) bonus points if the school site's chronic
22 absenteeism rate shows improvement.
23 I. The annual report shall identify the performance of each
24 school as having improved, remained the same, or declined. This
HB3151 HFLR Page 13
BOLD FACE denotes Committee Amendments.

1 scho ol improvement rating shall be based on a comparison of the
2 student and school performance data of the current year to the
3 previous year data.
4 J. The State Department of Education shall annually develop a
5 school site report card to be delivered to parents or legal
6 guardians throughout each school district. The report card shall be
7 in accordance with the requirements of the Elementary and Secondary
8 Education Act of 1965 (ESEA) as reauthorized and amended by P.L. No.
9 114-95, also known as the Every Student Succeeds Act (ESSA), and
10 include the grade for the school, information regarding school
11 improvement, an explanation of school performance, and indicators of
12 return on investment. The report card for each school site shall be
13 published annually by the Department on its website, and every
14 school district shall provide the school site report card to the
15 parent or legal guardian of each student enrolled in the school
16 site. In order to provide information regarding school performance
17 for school report cards issued during the 2016-2017 and 2017-2018
18 school years, the Department shall include an explanation of the
19 changes to the statewide system of student assessments as required
20 in Section 1210.508 of this title and how the transition in
21 assessments may impact school performance. The Department shall
22 issue school report cards using the 2016-2017 school year assessment
23 data that is available.
24
HB3151 HFLR Page 14
BOLD FACE denotes Committee Amendments.

1 K. The Legislature may factor in the performance of schools in
2 calculating any performance-based funding policy that is provided to
3 public school districts.
4 L. The State Board of Education shall amend the ESSA
5 consolidated State plan in accordance with the requirements of the
6 Every Student Succeeds Act (ESSA) to replace the measure of chronic
7 absenteeism to reflect the provisions of this section. The Board
8 shall submit the proposed amendment to the United States Department
9 of Education no later than August 1, 2025.
10 M. The State Board of Education shall promulgate rules to
11 implement the provisions of this section.
12 SECTION 3. This act shall become effective June 1, 2027.
